<TITLE> Some fear of flooding as river levels rise </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 17 (bdnews24.com)  Fear of flooding in some areas arose Sunday after the Flood Forecasting Warning Centre of the Water Development Board said waters at points of the Brahmaputra-Jamuna river basin are rising above danger levels. Executive engineer at FFWC Md Saiful Hossain told bdnews24.com: "A flood situation is not upon us yet. However the water levels are flowing above danger levels at seven points of the river basin." "It raises some fear of flooding in some areas over the next few days." "However, no such situation has yet been created for flood," Hossain stressed. Most parts of the country, including the capital Dhaka, was experiencing only light to moderate rainfall Sunday. Ten millimetres of rainfall was recorded in Dhaka up to 3pm Sunday, and the country's highest rainfall of 61mm was recorded at Feni up to noon. On duty forecast officer at the met office Md Rasheduzzaman told bdnews24.com: "The monsoon is active in most parts of the country. It is causing light to moderate rainfall in some areas. It will continue for the next two to three days." But FFWC's Hossain said moderate to heavy rainfall had been falling upstream of the main river basins of the country. According to the Indian Meteorological Department, Arunachal, Assam, Meghalaya, Bihar, Uttar Pradesh and the Ganges basin area have been experiencing heavy rainfall for the last few days causing rivers to rise. FFWC said the Padma was flowing above the danger mark at Pankha, Bhagyakul and Gualundo points; the Surma at Sunamganj; the Kangsha at Jariagonjail; the Arial Kha at Madaripur; and the Kushiara at Amolshid. Regarding the long term forecast for the month of August, director of the Bangladesh Meteorological Department Arjumand Habib said one or two seasonal low fronts may form over the rest of the month. "Overall the country may experience 10 to 15 per cent more rainfall than normal. There is apprehension of greater than usual flooding in the Ganges, Brahmaputra and Meghna basins during the last half of the month." bdnews
